  <static seed="1149" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions130.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{2}+9x+20}{-10x-x^{2}-25}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{x+4}{x+5}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors.</p>
<p>If a polynomial is not in order, we order it by the variable<rsq/>s degrees.</p>
<p>If the leading coefficient is negative, we factor out <m>-1</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{2}+9x+20}{-10x-x^{2}-25}} \amp = \frac{{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+5\right)}}{{-x^{2}-10x-25}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+5\right)}}{{-\left(x^{2}+10x+25\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{\left(x+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+5\right)}}{{-\left(x+5\right)^{2}}} \\
                     \amp = {-\frac{x+4}{x+5}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>x+5</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne -5</m>.</p>
</solution>
